"Abstract In September, in a change from my usual format in this series of articles on the changing face of international cryptography policy, I attempted to outline some of the more technical aspects of both RSA and its application to the field of Digital Signature. I did this by way of an example using very small numbers and a short numeric message, although the method would have worked just as well using very much larger numbers and a normal length message or identification code. Given the strong political push that has been given to this powerful technology by so many national administrations and international bodies, it is surely somewhat surprising that we have not yet seen it deployed more widely. Why should this be?"
